We now assume that organisms will adjust their activity level to maximise available energy relative to mortality $M$: $\tau_{\text{opt}}$ = $\max_\tau(F)$ = $\max_\tau(P_C/M)$, with $F$ a measure of fitness \footnote{I \emph{think} this amounts to maximizing R0 if no more growth occurs: life expectancy is 1/M and reporoductive output is proportional to energy}. We further assume here that mortality scales with activity level and weight as $w^{q-1}$ (\cite{andersen_how_2009, hartvig_food_2011}), such that $M_{\tau,w} = \tau^\eta \rho w^{q-1}$, where $ \rho$ is mortality at mass $w=1$ and $\tau=1$, that is, at constant maximum activity and $M$ is the effective mortality at realised levels of activity at weight $w$.

