Higher temperature have cascading effects through their influence on both metabolic and ecological rates (Figure \ref{fig:act_fig}). To maintain optimal energy aquisition for growth and reproduction relative to mortality, activity levels generally increase, until they reach limitations imposed by oxygen supply (Figure \ref{fig:act_fig}a). This limit occurs when active metabolic costs equal oxygen supply (Figure \ref{fig:act_fig}b), and are therefore more pronounced for species with strongly dome-shaped maximum-metabolic rates (scenario 3 in Figure \ref{fig:act_fig}).

